<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-475-014  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 475 014.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Journal of Systems and Software  April 1990 v12 n1 p71(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>U.S. Technology: we're losing the edge in software. (a relatedarticle provides an alternative view)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zucconi, Lin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US is losing its leadership in software technology and theinternational software market and must implement nationaltechnology policies to maintain its lead.andP;  Causes of decliningsoftware preeminence include lack of national consensus on theeconomic importance of science and technology with an emphasis oncomputer technology, little future-oriented investment in qualityscience and mathematics education, a desire by many to reviveheavy industry and agriculture, lack of emphasis on quality,excess emphasis on 'quick-fix' solutions to long-term problems,and the vigorous pursuit of computer and software technologies byPacific Rim nations.andP;  A US computer and software technology policyshould include a new cabinet-level Department of Technology andInformation; a national science, math and technology program;aggressive software research and development; and a focus onsoftware quality.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United StatesPolicySoftware PublishersImpact AnalysisPerformance ImprovementIndustry AnalysisForeign CompetitionRequirements AnalysisAsia.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>